Each Wednesday the high school counselors will be sending out helpful information to ALL high school students via email. The name of these emails will be "Riveting Wednesday Information." At the beginning of the month in our monthly newsletter sent out to students, staff, and parents, you will find the topics we will be covering. This information will be shared through various platforms including videos, slideshows, and some interactive slideshows.

The topics for this month are:
Wednesday, September 9: A Student's Guide to Learning from Home

Wednesday, September 16: Relationship skills

Wednesday, September 23: Strategies for Sustaining your well being: how long will this go on?

Wednesday, September 30: Career Planning: EDP checklist for each grade

In support of Fruitport's esteemed athletic director, Ken Erny, who was diagnosed with ALS earlier this summer, please consider supporting the family.

Ken's daughter, Jess, has set up a team page on the ALS of MI walk website called HIKE FOR HOPE. Due to COVID-19, an in-person walk will not be held, but you may still participate virtually by:
donating to a team member or signing up as a team member and fund raising in honor of Ken.

THANK YOU for your support!

http://web.alsa.org/site/TR?fr_id=14326&pg=team&team_id=391378

post_text:
Our graduation ceremony will be held at the Doc Pierce Football Stadium on Thursday, July 30 at 6:00 p.m. (with a rain date of Friday, July 31 at 6:00 p.m.) Participating seniors must attend a mandatory graduation practice on July 30 at 9:30 a.m. at the football stadium. Due to COVID-19 social-distancing guidelines, seniors will be given two tickets to distribute to family members. Tickets must be limited to two per family to meet the 25% capacity requirement. Again, social distancing protocols will be followed and please remember that face coverings should be worn.

We are hoping for a live stream of this event and will keep you posted with further information. Congratulations Class of 2020! This is a well-deserved accomplishment!!

High School Students and Parents:

We will offer three more opportunities for underclassmen (9-11) to turn in their chromebooks, textbooks, library books, band/choir/athletic uniforms, etc. and for seniors to pick up award packets (there is an envelope for every senior). You or your student can come to the front doors of the high school near the electronic sign on Tuesday, June 30 from 9:00 - 11:00 a.m. or Wednesday, July 1 from Noon - 2:00 p.m. or 5:00 - 7:00 p.m.

Seniors will want these packets for their open houses so please come to see us during one of these time slots.

post_text:
High School students,
As the year comes to a close, we hope youâ€™ll begin to plan for next fall. If you have any interest in a healthcare career and may consider becoming a doctor, there is a free program we encourage you to consider.

West Michigan OsteoScholars brings together local resources to help students of all backgrounds to understand, prepare for, and navigate the path to becoming a physician. It is free and open to anyone with a 3.0 GPA or above.

If you think medical school is too hard or too expensive for you, you might be surprised at how many resources are available to help you. Give it a try! Meetings are held just once a month and youâ€™ll be introduced to area physician mentors, resume-building experiences, and you can even try your hand at medical procedures at the Mercy Health Regional Simulation Lab.

https://osteopathicfoundation.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/2020-WM-OsteoScholars-Application-June-1.pdf

The application deadline is June 1 and the form is simple, so get your application in soon.

post_text:
The Fruitport Fire Police Department would like to honor Fruitport's Class of 2020 on Friday May 8th with a show of lights. The department is encouraging seniors to decorate their cars and wear their caps and gowns as they drive through the police/fire department parking lot from 8:00 - 8:20 p.m. Senior cars should enter via the Mt. Garfield entrance to the department, drive through the lot, and exit onto Airline Road. Police and fire personnel will be on site to direct traffic.

We hope you participate in this event.

Mrs. Chesney and Mr. Rogers

Muskegon Area Promise Scholarship
April 16 at 6:43 PM Â·

UPDATE (April): All MAISD programs and buildings will be closed through the remainder of the academic year. This closure includes the office of the Promise.

All 12th grade eligible Promise Scholars will be notified by US mail on or around May 1, 2020. This date has been delayed by two weeks. In a mailing that was hopeful for this week (4/17), we have learned we needed to gather more details from our state and local schools first.

Award acceptance will still need to occur by our strict deadline of July 1, 2020.

Stay healthy, and please do not hesitate to reach out to me with any questions.

mbyard@muskegonisd.org

post_text:
Tonight we celebrated the Fruitport High School Class of 2020 by lighting up the Doc Pierce Fruitport Stadium for 20 minutes and 20 seconds. We did this to honor our seniors and celebrate all that they have accomplished.

While we recognize there was much that went unfinished for these seniors including the spring musical, the spring sports season, the Excellence in Education banquet, and so many more events and opportunities, we want them to know in a show of pride and unity that the Fruitport community is behind them and supports them. In the face of extreme adversity, these seniors will forever shine as brightly as our stadium lights in the heart of the Fruitport community.

GO BLUE!!

post_text:
Tonight the Doc Pierce Fruitport Stadium lights will be turned on from 9:00 - 9:20 p.m. to honor the Fruitport High School Class of 2020. There is so much that they have missed out on because of this school closure that we want to shine a light on and celebrate all they have accomplished.

Please note that we are not inviting anyone to congregate at the stadium or on school property. We will post pictures of the lit stadium later this evening. We encourage you to participate in this celebration by turning your porch lights on tonight in support of the senior class.

Together we will LIGHT IT UP FOR BLUE!!

Today we honor senior Kamden Sweet. Kam was our starting center fielder last year as a junior. Kam would have been a two year starter this year in the outfield. He like many of our players is versatile to play infield and outfield when needed. He also is a relief pitcher. Kam as soon as last year was done was right back working on his skills. He made huge strides in all areas and was looking to have a huge year at the plate and in the field. Kam would have been an innings eater out of our bullpen this year and be very successful at it. Kam is a teammate thatâ€™s wants nothing more than to see his buddies succeed and his team to do well. He would do anything a coach would ask. Chase a ball out of play heâ€™s on it. Drag the tarp on it. Kamâ€™s leadership and love for the game will be missed by all. Kam plans on attending MCC in the fall. We will miss Kamâ€™s leadership, hard work, and just the pure joy that he brings to the field everyday. Thank You Kam from the bottom of our hearts for all you have done for the Fruitport baseball program, and the future Fruitport Trojan baseballers. Go Blue.

shared_text:
Nick Reedâ€ŽFruitport High School Trojan Baseball
April 9 at 12:35 PM Â·

Today we are honoring Chase R. Campbell. Or as we like to call him Soup. Chase would have been a second year starter on the Varsity as a DH/corner infielder. Like so many of our players he is versatile enough to play multiple positions and be effective. Chase took advantage of his opportunities when he was thrust into the line up due to some injuries and never looked back. He hit .333 in 17 games as a junior with a .462 on base percentage. Chase batted in the 5th spot and provided protection for Luke and Nick. He also hit .400 in conference games. If teams pitched around them they had to pitch to Chase and he often made them pay. Chase put a lot of work in during the off-season and was primed for a big season. Chase is quiet and often lets his game do his talking but he is also quick to protect his teammates. Chase plans on attending MCC in the fall. We are gonna miss Chase next year and the leadership and work ethic he brought to the program. Thank you from the Bottom of our hearts Chase and thank you for all you have done for Fruitport Baseball. Go Blue.

Nick Reedâ€ŽFruitport High School Trojan Baseball
April 7 at 12:49 PM Â·

Our second senior to be honored is David Ross. David would have been a second year starter as a senior. As a junior he started at multiple spots. Heâ€™s played Shortstop,third,second,all 3 outfield spots and this year he was working on the mound as a reliever for us as well. David is the type of kid that if the coaches asked him to do something with out hesitation he would say yes coach. He is a true program guy. David as a junior hit .296 overall .347 in league play. He had an on base percentage of .387. David scored 24 runs with 9 runs batted in with 5 doubles. David led the team last year with 15 stolen bases. David is always willing to help another teammate to get better. David plans on attending Alma in the fall where he plans to study Computer Science and then Biotec Engineering and to play football. David sports 3.3 GPA. We will miss Davidâ€™s drive and enthusiasm next year. Thank You for all you have done for the program and good luck in future endeavors. Go Blue.

shared_text:
Nick Reedâ€ŽFruitport High School Trojan Baseball
April 6 at 1:01 PM Â·

First senior to be honored is Brodie Boes. Brodie was pulled up as a sophomore to fill in on the mound against Allendale who was the returning regional champions. Brodie pitches great and lost a heart breaker 6-5 in the bottom of the 7th. He finished his sophomore year on varsity with 12 innings pitched 5.6 ERA and a 1-1 record. He followed up with his junior year going 2-4 on the mound with 3.39 ERA and a No Hitter against Muskegon. 30 strikeouts in 33 innings pitched. Brodie was primed to have a huge year his senior year. Brodie has a demeanor on the mound coaches love. Nothing phases him and heâ€™s always looking for the next pitch to finish off the batter. Brodie loves the outdoors and is often fishing in his free time. We are gonna miss Brodie next year and the experience he brought to the team. Brodie plans to attend MCC next year and take electrical courses. Thank you from the bottom of our hearts Brodie and good luck with your future endeavors. Go Blue.

Pre-Packaged Meals:

As you are aware, beginning March 16 Fruitport Community Schools will be closed until April 6th. To assist families in need, the districtâ€™s food service program will be providing pre-packaged lunches for school-aged children who reside or attend schools in our district. The meals may be picked up in the following locations:

Families of Edgewood, FMS & FHS Students:
The student parking lot between FHS and Edgewood Elementary School.

Families of Beach & Shettler Elementary Students:
The west parking lot of Shettler Elementary school.

To estimate how many meals we need to have prepared and to determine how many meals should be sent to each location, please complete the form found on the district website.

More information and updates regarding this program, including distribution times & dates, will be made available on the district website.

Please complete this survey by Monday, March 16th, to ensure we have an accurate count of needed meals.

The FEF has partnered with the FHS Athletic Department to revise the Athletic Hall of Fame. It will now be known as the Fruitport Hall of Fame. In addition to Athletic Achievement, which honors athletes, coaches & athletic service personnel, two new categories have been added:

*Academic / Career Accomplishments (includes military recognition)
*Service to FCS (need not be a FHS alumnus - includes individuals, businesses and/or organizations)

Nomination forms are available online at the link below. Hard copy forms are available at each school office.

If you know of a deserving individual, team or group that you feel should be considered, please complete the nomination form. The deadline for 2020 nominations is Friday, May 1. The 2020 induction ceremony will take place in the new Fruitport Performing Arts Center on Saturday, October 3, 2020.

For further information, contact the athletic office at 231-865-4035.

http://bit.ly/HOFNominationForm

post_text: Homeless students from across Muskegon County will soon benefit from The Gear Group's #BeTheGoodLoveWins campaign. Clothing sales and staff donations generated $850 for hats, gloves, mittens, and wool socks. The items will be distributed through the Muskegon Area Intermediate School District and each district's homeless liaison. Pictured left to right: Riley Sokolow (Gear Group), Kristin Tank (MAISD), Superintendent John Severson (MAISD), Vice President Shan Bonjernoor (Gear Group), April Aebig (Gear Group), and Carolyn Lash (Gear Group). Each quarter a new beneficiary is chosen. This quarter all proceeds will go to Pound Buddies of Muskegon.

post_text: Last night Shettler students spoke about a new program in their school. "Shettler Families" was created to bring students from all grade levels together a couple times per month to work on positive behavior curriculum and various projects as a "family". Each family is led by a staff member, has a family name, and a secret handshake. The families will stay together until they leave the building, adding new kindergartners each year.

post_text:
Southside Lacrosse is excited to announce that we are starting an all Muskegon area Girls Youth Lacrosse Program for girls in 5th, 6th, 7th & 8th grades. We will be hosting a FREE beginner clinic Wednesday, Jan 22 5:00-6:30 @ Lakeshore Athletic Center in Muskegon on Airline Rd.

This is a basic skill clinic where we will be coaching fundamentals like passing, catching, scooping, cradling and shooting. The clinic will be coached by experienced Girls Lax Coaches and some high school players. Gear (sticks) will be provided for those who need them.

Girls Lacrosse is the fastest growing sport in North America at the youth, High School and College levels. The Southside Girls Program will feed the Mona Shores and Reeths-Puffer MHSAA sanctioned Varsity teams.

Please pass this email and the attached flyer along to your friends and anyone who might be interested in trying girls lacrosse this spring. Feel free to contact Coach Greer directly with any questions or concerns. We look forward to seeing you there.

Email Coach Greer @ murle.greer@gmail.com to register.

On behalf of the Trojan Travelers, we are hosting a casino bus trip on February 8 to the Gun Lake Casino. Adam Carlson will be the emcee.

The bus will leave Orchard Market at 3 pm and is expected to return at 9 pm. Tickets are $30 each and include a $10 food voucher and $10 game credit. Beverages and snacks are allowed on the bus. There will be door prizes and a 50/50 raffle.

If you are interested in purchasing tickets, or would like to donate items for door prizes, please contact Tammy at truch@fruitportschools.net or Tracy at tbordewyk@fruitportschools.net.

Thank you for your support!
Tammy & Tracy

I was recently asked about depositing money into the E-Link lunch program. There must have been a recent update to the software, as it is different. Here's how to deposit funds into your student's account:

1. Log Into E-Link

2. In the upper left, you will see "Site Navigation" with an arrow pointing down.

3. Hover your mouse over that, and it will expand with three choices, the second one is to deposit funds.

If you have any issues, please contact Zach Zost our Food Service Director and he will help you out.

post_text:
CONGRATULATIONS High School Students of the Month:
Erika Burgess-12th Grade
Erika is the daughter of Tim and Tracy Burgess. Erika is overall undecided on which college she will attend, but is choosing between Central Michigan University, Michigan State University, and Grand Valley State University. She plans to pursue a degree in English education. She has played four years of volleyball, is a member of NHS and Spanish Club, and has participated in 5 of the annual musicals. In her free time, Erika loves spending time with her friends and family, camping, and writing.

Cooper Somers-12th Grade
Cooper is the son of Wendy Somers and John Somers. He would like to attend the University of Michigan in order to study mathematics. Cooper has been a member of the marching band for four years, and he has been the drum major of the marching band for two. He also participates in the quiz bowl and jazz band.

Thank you for supporting the Fruitport Lions Club food drive.

post_text:
Craig Hillier Presentation for All Winter Sports Athletes and Parents

FMS Auditorium Thursday November 7th, 7:00 pm

Please plan to attend the All School Winter Sport Parent and Player meeting taking place Thursday evening November 7 at the FMS Auditorium. Our guest, Craig Hillier, is a nationally known motivational speaker and author. Craig offers a one-hour session on the topic of student leadership and improving the sports culture. His presentation promises to be high energy and entertaining. Following that session, winter coaches will host breakout sessions giving details on the upcoming winter season. For those attending, there will be a special drawing for sports passes to this winter's events.

Regardless of what season or sport, this is a worthwhile time for all our student athletes and parents.

post_text:
Congratulations to our October High School Students of the Month, Nick Piper and Amaya Simmons-Secord.

Nick Piper-12th Grade
Nick is the son of Tom and Kelli Piper. Nick plans on attending either Kettering University or Michigan Tech to pursue a degree in electrical engineering. He has played 2 years of soccer, is a member of NHS, has participated on the robotics team for 4 years and works part time at Ram Electronics. In his free time, Nick enjoys spending time with friends, and family as well as volunteering.

Amaya Simmons-Secord-12th Grade
Amaya is the daughter of Trish Secord and Teresa Schooley. Amaya plans on attending Lake Superior State University next fall to pursue a degree in science. In her free time, she enjoys drawing, photography, and reading.

post_text:
This weekend was our last regular season marching band competition. Unfortunately, our performance was rained out and we performed a "stand still" performance, which does not count towards State Finals. However, based on how the rest of the season has gone, I am thrilled to announce that we have qualified for State Finals and are currently sitting at 5th place out of 13! We will be traveling to Ford Field this upcoming Saturday to compete at Ford Field.

This has been a great season for these kids and Katie and I are very proud of their hard work. Our Stadium Echoes performance is next Monday, November 4th at 7pm for anyone who wants to see the show, one last time after State Finals.

Thank you again for your support during these last few months! We are excited to see how these kids do on Saturday! - Tim Priest

post_text: During Safety Week the district practices multiple drills such as evacuation, tornado, lockdowns, and fire drills. Today's evacuation DRILL was a success. All Edgewood students and staff arrived safely to the evacuation site in 13 minutes. If, for whatever reason, the building is unsafe, students know where to go, under the direction of their teacher and principal. Thank you to our School Resource Officer for making sure everyone was safe. GREAT WORK!

shared_text:
Fruitport Robotics Team 2405
October 6, 2019 at 3:19 AM Â·

Our Techno Trojans ladies had an awesome day Saturday at the Grand Rapids Girls Robotics Competition! After qualifying rounds found themselves as the #6 Alliance Captains and picked great partners with 2771 Code Red Robotics and MARS Rovers 4004. They made it to the finals against the powerful #1 Alliance of Stryke Force 4-H FIRST Robotics Team 2767, FRC Team 6591 Panther Powered - Stockbridge, MI, and The Atomics 5256 - FIRST Robotics from Lake Odessa. After loosing the first match to the #1 Alliance, our #6 Alliance came back with a good defensive strategy to then win the next two matches and take home the blue T-Rex trophies. Congratulations to all the teams for competing well and showing what girl power can do!

post_text:
Monday, September 23, 2019 at 7:00 p.m.
Fruitport Middle School - Auditorium

You and your student-athlete are invited to hear national renowned Recruiting Expert Jack Renkens. I'm confident you will find Jack's presentation educational, informative and entertaining. It will be a great one-hour investment of time for you and your student-athlete. Parents all over the country are raving about the importance and impact of this presentation.

Jack is entering his 23rd year touring the United States, has been featured on numerous TV and radio shows across the country and will be at our school on:

We have made an investment on behalf of our parents, student-athletes and community for this seminar on the realities of college recruiting. You will learn from Jack the unique financial opportunities available to student-athletes like yours.

This event is designed for every high school parent and their student-athlete. To get a snapshot of the presentation, visit www.recruitingrealities.com and click on video clips.

We look forward to seeing you there.
